occupatio, the advisedly taking possession os an object which has no owner (res nullius) with the intention of appropriating it. The following kinds of res nullius are mentioned in the text: wild animals, birds, and ’ fishes, §i 12-16: enemies’ property, § 17: stones and pebbles found on the seashore,§ 18: islands rising in the sea, § 22 : treasure-trove, ξ 39: and res derelictae, ξ 47. The Romans had no game laws, which in England grew out of feudalism and the great sorests ot the Norman kings and nobility. Some writers have maintained the contrary, but Dig. 47. 10. 13. 7 is explicit to the effect that the landowner can prevent others (even by soree, Cic. pro Caec. 8, Dig.43. 16. 3. 9) from coming on his land, but not from exercising occupatio when there. lt would seem from the text that express notice not to enter was necessary to constitute a trespass in every case.
